6 Experimental Evaluation
We evaluate the proposed Maximum Entropy relaxation on a family of NPORS-derived scaling benchmarks with ternary-or-less cardinality constraints. The goal is to isolate how relative performance changes with the number of attributes, the constraint arity, and the sampled population size.
6.1 Experimental Setup
To obtain realistic yet controllable instances, we use the 2024 National Public Opinion Reference Survey (NPORS) as a source population. After preprocessing, the dataset contains respondents and several hundred categorical or discretized variables with explicit missing-value codes.
We construct five NPORS-derived problems by selecting subsets of categorical attributes with moderate domain sizes, clear semantic interpretation, and limited structural missingness. Each subset induces an empirical population in the formalism of Section 3, from which we extract global cardinality constraints over attribute patterns of increasing arity:
-
•
Unary constraints, corresponding to marginal distributions of single attributes;
-
•
Binary constraints, corresponding to joint marginals over pairs of attributes;
-
•
Ternary constraints, corresponding to joint marginals over triples of attributes.
Unary marginals are always included in full. For , all candidate pairs and triples are retained. For , binary and ternary interactions are ranked by informativeness and truncated to the top 50 pairs and top 50 triples, respectively. This keeps the benchmark family comparable across problem sizes while allowing the number of atomic constraints to reflect domain size and interaction complexity.
