The algorithm outputs a constraint problem defined by a set of global Sum constraints enforcing exact pattern counts for the selected marginals. The total number of atomic constraints equals the sum of the number of observed values across all selected attributes, pairs, and triples — which may be orders of magnitude larger than the number of selected variable pairs or triples (e.g., 50 triples yielding up to 17 883 atomic constraints for a 40-variable problem).
